'''Do-It-Yourself book scanning''' is using cheap, compact cameras and free open source software to scan books quickly and efficiently. DIY Book Scanners can be as simple as a [http://www.instructables.com/id/Bargain-Price-Book-Scanner-From-A-Cardboard-Box/ camera and a piece of glass] [http://diybookscanner.org/PDF/Bargain-Price-Book-Scanner-From-A-Cardboard-Box.pdf PDF] or as involved as the [http://www.instructables.com/id/DIY-High-Speed-Book-Scanner-from-Trash-and-Cheap-C/ Instructable that brought our community together] [http://diybookscanner.org/PDF/DIY-High-Speed-Book-Scanner-from-Trash-and-Cheap-C.pdf PDF] / [http://vimeo.com/4219953 Vimeo]. Today the DIY book scanning community has GPL-licensed [http://www.diybookscanner.org/news/?p=66 laser cut designs], [http://diybookscanner.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=1&t=495 aluminum designs], and [http://www.diybookscanner.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=1&t=333 detailed instructions for beginners]. They have built hundreds of [http://www.diybookscanner.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=4&t=375 scanners] and freely shared [http://www.diybookscanner.org/forum/viewtopic.php?f=1&t=280 thousands of design improvements].

This type of technology is useful to the [[OSAT]] community to digitize out of print [[appropriate technology]] books, [[wikipedia:Wikipedia:Glossary#Wikify|wikify]] them, and then share them here.

